<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-01-08T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-01-08T12:00:00-05:00" n="976" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d976">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.731/218</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-08T17:00:00+00:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 8, 1915, 5 p. m.</hi>
                                </date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7.15 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1437. The stopping of commercial cables, I am sorry to say, continues in
                            perhaps a slightly diminished number, but from forty to sixty a day are
                            stopped out of perhaps ten thousand. The chief cause given is suspicion
                            of technical commercial terms. I continue to insist on employment of men
                            who know these terms, especially in the cotton trade. But I am afraid
                            that it will be necessary to inform our commercial bodies and
                            telegraphic companies that the exclusion of every technical word from
                            telegrams will help more than anything else.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>